        title: "The right work fits who you already are",
        text:
          "Some coworkers make you feel at home from the very first day. Others leave you searching for a new approach each morning. The difference often comes down to how well the role matches the principles and values you carry inside. Many of us never stop to name those inner drivers. The Swiss psychologist Carl Jung spent years trying to answer that question. He believed people fall into clear patterns that shape how they think and act. Two American researchers, Isabel Briggs Myers and her mother Katharine Briggs, built on Jung's work. They created the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator, often shortened to MBTI. The MBTI sorts people into sixteen different personality types.\n\nYou can find your type in two ways. The first is to take the official MBTI test and then meet with a career counselor who is trained to read the results. The second is to walk yourself through the four core dimensions at your own pace. Both paths lead to the same place. The MBTI rests on four opposite pairs. They cover where you get your energy, how you take in information, how you make decisions, and how you live your daily life. The first pair is extraversion, marked E, and introversion, marked I. Extraverts recharge by talking with others. Introverts recharge by spending quiet time alone. The second pair is sensing, marked S, and intuition, marked N. Sensors trust what their five senses tell them. Intuitives look for patterns and meaning behind the facts. The third pair is thinking, marked T, and feeling, marked F. Thinkers weigh choices with logic. Feelers weigh choices with empathy. The fourth pair is judging, marked J, and perceiving, marked P. Judgers prefer order and firm plans. Perceivers prefer flexibility and open options.\n\nOnce you know where you fall on each pair, you can look up the profile that matches your four-letter code. That profile gives you a fuller picture of how your mind works at work.",
