        text:
          "Suffering is often a choice, and that sentence can sound strange. Who in their right mind would choose to suffer. You may push back on the idea, yet it holds up under a closer look. Buddhists tell a story about two arrows. The first arrow is the event itself, the loss, the illness, the setback that lands on you without warning. The second arrow is your reaction to the event, and that second arrow almost always hurts more than the first. Imagine that you lose your job. You can see it as a personal failure, and that story can drag you into a long stretch of depression. Or you can see it as a turning point, a chance to find a better fit. The first reading pulls you down. The second reading sets you free to look around. The choice between those two readings is yours, and it shapes the rest of your life. A good place to start is to forgive yourself for the past and put your energy into what comes next. This summary will show you how to master your own mind and free up space for inspiration. The goal is to live more and to think less.",
