          "No movie tells the story of a calm and happy life. Audiences want struggle, pain, sacrifice, and a hard-won win. Drama is wired into our biology. Think of the last book you loved. If it had no conflict, you probably grew bored by the second chapter. The same craving for drama shows up in daily life. Mundane routines can sting more than big setbacks, because they leave you with no clear enemy to fight. The fear of growing past old friends and old comforts can also keep you stuck. Leaving a tired job or a tired friendship is scary, and the fear of change can lock you in place. Write a to-do list to organize your thoughts and ease some anxiety. Once you learn to live in the zone of non-thinking, you will notice a quieter head and a few hidden strengths. The first is that you stop sorting events into good and bad. You welcome each moment as it comes. Most of the trouble in life comes from the labels we stick on events. The second is that you learn a wider form of truth. A storm that ruins a beach day is a gift to a farmer praying for rain. The same event can mean very different things to two people. The third is that you hear your intuition. That quiet voice often points toward your truest wants. Many people lose the signal under a pile of worry. Listening to it pays off, even when the road feels strange.",
